I currently have:

Wheat 14×5 = 70  
Wood 25×10 = 250  
Sheep 14×18 = 252  
Brick 23×28 = 644  
Ore 10×39 = 390  
Total value ≈ 1 606

Observation: Ore and Brick are the only resources that actually increase in value (39, 28). Every other resource is worth less than they show above (I already hold the lowest-value versions). Net value decrease every time I give up Ore/Brick for anything else.

Therefore the winning path is:
1. Acquire more Ore & Brick.
2. Never give away Ore or Brick.
3. Push everything else aggressively.

Ideal price anchored to the difference between the opponent’s and my marginal value:
- Ore: I value it 39, you presumably less.  
- Brick: I value it 28, you presumably less.  
- Sheep: I value it 18, you presumably less.  
- Wood: I value it 10, you presumably less.  
- Wheat: I value it 5, you presumably less.

Hence the most valuable surplus I can dangle early is Sheep/Brick, since I have plenty of each.

Next offer:  
I extract more Ore and Brick by dangling the best “cheap” high-quantity good I have—a quasi-bulk of Sheep at 18 that the opponent probably likes more than I do.

[Offer: 6 Sheep, 3 Brick, 1 Wheat -> 5 Ore, 3 Brick]
(offer 6 low-value Sheep plus “change” to net-gain 2 Ore and stay even on Brick)
